But what happens if there are multiple interpretations?

The query model skews towards the dominant results leading to higher scores for results supporting the dominant interpretation.

Using these scores, we filter out documents that do not support the dominant interpretation.

We observe our own index so we can compute the most ‚Äúimportant‚Äù terms for each document. This becomes the content used to expand the query model.

With this expanded query model, we can re-score the top k results.

The key insight underpinning our approach is pseudo-relevance feedback (PRF).

Explained simply, you retrieve & rank to find the top k results for a query.

Then assuming these results are all relevant to the query, you expand your query model using the contents of these results. https://t.co/pTxfyyaUU3

If you've already evaluated the query, check django.db.connections.queries instead:

>>> from django.db import connection
>>> connection.queries[-1]["sql"]
SELECT "users_user"."id", "users_user"."email", "users_user"."password" FROM "users_user" WHERE "users_user"."is_admin"

Want to know want SQL a #Django queryset will run?

Convert its "query" attribute to a string:

>>> qs = User.objects.filter(is_admin=True)
>>> print(qs.query)
SELECT "users_user"."id", "users_user"."email", "users_user"."password" FROM "users_user" WHERE "users_user"."is_admin"

2) The Graph

Indexers are node operators in The Graph Network that stake Graph Tokens (GRT) in order to provide indexing and query processing services.

Indexers earn query fees and indexing rewards for their services.

Because indexers can immediately filter and process data according to defined requirements, they can simplify the wide query execution.

For example, a stream of data can be written to a permanent database for later analysis using a convenient query language like SQL.
However, querying data across many blocks can be cumbersome because we have to aggregate results from multiple single-block queries. Therefore, we can consider these wide queries.

To understand why this is important, we must consider blockchain basics.

Blockchain data is optimized for serialized¬†writes, one block at a time, as the chain is being created. Querying the blockchain for data about a specific block is fairly straightforward or a narrow query.

Indexers are, in a simple form, node operators. 

They extract, transform and load data into databases by mapping the data into a pre-defined schema of tables in order to provide indexing and query processing services via the API.
